Based on possible world semantics, we define a frame F = 〈W,B,D, I, E〉 as a tuple where:
• W is a nonempty set of possible worlds,
• B : AGT → (W → 2W ) is the function that associates each agent a ∈ AGT and possible world w ∈W to the set of belief-accessible worlds Ba(w),
• D : AGT → (W ×DEG+ → 2W ) is the function that associates each agent a ∈ AGT and possible world w ∈ W with a level of desirability l ∈ DEG+ to the set of desire-accessible worlds Da(w, l),
• I : AGT → (W → 2W ) is the function that associates each agent a ∈ AGT and possible world w ∈W to the set of intention-accessible worlds Ia(w), and
• E : EV T → W is the function that associates each event ∈ EV T to the resulting possible world.
Then, a model M = 〈F ,V〉 is a couple where F is a frame and V : W → ATM a valuation function.
Given a model M we note M, w |= ϕ a formula ϕ that is true in a world w. Truth conditions of formulas are defined by induction in the classical way:
• M, w |= p iff p ∈ V(w);
• M, w |= ¬ϕ iff not M, w |= ϕ;
• M, w |= ϕ ∧ ψ iff M, w |= ϕ and M, w |= ψ ;
• M, w |= Bella(ϕ) iff card(GBa(w))card(Ba(w)) = l where GBa(w) = {v ∈ Ba(w) ; M, v |= ϕ} ;
• M, w |= Desla(ϕ) iff M, v |= ϕ ∀v ∈ Da(w, l);
• M, w |= Inta(ϕ) iff M, v |= ϕ ∀v ∈ Ia(w);
• M, w |= iff M, v |= > ∀v ∈ E( );
The truth condition ofBella(ϕ) states that the level of plausibility of ϕ is the proportion of belief-accessible worlds where ϕ is true. The next subsections describe the rules for the inference engines presented in section 3. When required, the computation of believability, desirability and intensity degrees will be represented by a f function that is part of the implementation and will not be detailed in this section (see section 5 instead).
